        <section class="prose">
          <h2>What is horsepower to weight ratio?</h2>
          <p>
            Horsepower to weight ratio (also called <strong>power-to-weight ratio</strong>) compares how much power an engine produces to how much mass it has to move. It is one of the best single numbers to describe how fast a car, bike, or truck can accelerate.
          </p>
          <p>
            In simple terms, more horsepower and less weight give a higher ratio and usually better performance.
          </p>

          <h3>Horsepower to weight ratio formulas</h3>
          <div class="formula-box">
            <p><strong>Using metric units (hp and kg):</strong></p>
            <p>\[
              \text{hp per kg} = \frac{\text{power (hp)}}{\text{weight (kg)}}
            \]</p>
            <p><strong>hp per metric ton:</strong></p>
            <p>\[
              \text{hp per ton} = \frac{\text{power (hp)}}{\text{weight (kg)} / 1000}
              = \frac{\text{power (hp)} \times 1000}{\text{weight (kg)}}
            \]</p>
            <p><strong>Using imperial units (hp and lb):</strong></p>
            <p>\[
              \text{hp per lb} = \frac{\text{power (hp)}}{\text{weight (lb)}}
            \]</p>
            <p><strong>Weight per horsepower (lb/hp):</strong></p>
            <p>\[
              \text{lb per hp} = \frac{\text{weight (lb)}}{\text{power (hp)}}
            \]</p>
          </div>

          <p>
            The calculator converts all inputs internally to <strong>hp</strong> and <strong>kg</strong>, then computes every ratio consistently.
          </p>

          <h3>Unit conversions used</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>1 kW = 1.34102 hp</li>
            <li>1 PS (metric hp) = 0.73549875 kW ≈ 0.98632 hp</li>
            <li>1 kg = 2.20462 lb</li>
            <li>1 metric ton = 1000 kg</li>
            <li>1 US short ton = 2000 lb</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>How to use the horsepower to weight ratio calculator</h2>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Enter engine power</strong> in hp, kW, or PS.</li>
            <li><strong>Enter vehicle weight</strong> in kg, lb, metric tons, or US short tons.</li>
            <li>Click <strong>Calculate</strong> to see hp/ton, hp/kg, hp/lb, kW/kg, and lb/hp.</li>
            <li>Use the <strong>Swap</strong> button if you want to think in terms of weight per horsepower (lb/hp) instead of hp/ton.</li>
            <li>Optionally, click a <strong>preset</strong> (hot hatch, sports car, supercar, superbike) to see typical values.</li>
          </ol>

          <h2>Typical horsepower to weight ratio ranges</h2>
          <p>These are rough guidelines for <strong>hp per metric ton</strong> (hp/ton):</p>
          <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-gray-100">
                <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Vehicle type</th>
                <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Approx. hp/ton</th>
                <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Typical example</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Economy car</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">60–100 hp/ton</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Small city car, base compact sedan</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Family / midsize car</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">90–140 hp/ton</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Typical 4‑cyl midsize sedan or crossover</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Hot hatch / warm sports sedan</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">140–200 hp/ton</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">GTI‑class hot hatch, entry sports sedan</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Sports car</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">200–260 hp/ton</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Modern V6/V8 sports coupes</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Supercar</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">260–350+ hp/ton</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">High‑end supercars, some hypercars</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-3 py-2">Superbike</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2">500–900+ hp/ton</td>
                <td class="px-3 py-2">1000 cc sport bikes, literbikes</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <h2>Interpreting your result</h2>
          <p>
            A higher horsepower to weight ratio generally means:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Stronger acceleration (better 0–60 mph / 0–100 km/h).</li>
            <li>More responsive overtaking and highway passing.</li>
            <li>Potentially higher top speed (with suitable gearing and aerodynamics).</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            However, real performance also depends on traction, gearing, torque curve, aerodynamics, and driver skill. Two cars with the same hp/ton can feel very different.
          </p>

          <h3>Horsepower to weight vs torque to weight</h3>
          <p>
            Horsepower to weight is best for comparing <strong>overall performance</strong>, especially at higher speeds. Torque to weight can be more relevant for low‑rpm pull, towing, or off‑road driving. For a complete picture, consider both.
          </p>

          <h2>FAQ</h2>

          <h3>What is a good horsepower to weight ratio for a daily driver?</h3>
          <p>
            For a comfortable daily driver, <strong>90–140 hp/ton</strong> is perfectly adequate. This covers most modern compact and midsize cars and allows safe merging and overtaking without feeling slow.
          </p>

          <h3>Is 200 hp per ton fast?</h3>
          <p>
            Yes. Around <strong>200 hp/ton</strong> is where cars start to feel genuinely quick. Many hot hatches and entry‑level sports cars live in this range, often delivering 0–60 mph in the 5–6 second bracket.
          </p>

          <h3>Why do motorcycles have such high power-to-weight ratios?</h3>
          <p>
            Motorcycles are extremely light compared to cars. A 200 hp superbike that weighs 200 kg has about <strong>1000 hp/ton</strong>, far beyond most road cars. That’s why even mid‑range bikes can out‑accelerate powerful cars.
          </p>

          <h3>Should I use curb weight or race weight?</h3>
          <p>
            Use <strong>curb weight</strong> to compare manufacturer specs. Use <strong>race weight</strong> (vehicle + driver + fuel + gear) if you care about real‑world or track performance. The calculator works with either; just be consistent when comparing vehicles.
          </p>
        </section>
